                    <msContents>
                        <summary>An undated, anonymous Persian translation of the Four Books of the
                            Gospels, Matthew, Mark, Luke and John. </summary>
                        <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_976-item1">
                            <editor role="trl" key="person_f407">
                                <persName>Anonymous</persName>
                            </editor>
                            <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_8361">Tarjumah-'i Chahār
                                Kitāb-i Injīl</title>
                            <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_8361">ترجمهٔ چهار کتاب انجیل</title>
                            <title xml:lang="en" type="desc" key="work_8361">Persian Translation of
                                the Four Gospels</title>

                            <explicit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="216b" to="216b"> برگ ۲۱۶پ (folio
                                    216b):</locus> حضرت عیسی پسر خداست و اینجا اندک سخن آورده شد
                                برای نمودار که آسان شود خوانندگان را برای یافتن و پیدا کردن این
                                راست. </explicit>
                            <colophon> No colophon</colophon>
                            <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                            <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_976-item1-item1">
                                <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus>
                                <title key="work_702">The Gospel of St. Matthew</title>
                                <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="beginning">
                                    <locus from="1a" to="1a"> برگ ۱ر (folio 1a):</locus> کتاب نسبت
                                    عیسی مسیح ابن داودبن ابراهیم از ابراهیم بوجود آمد. ابراهیم اسحاق
                                    را زاده اسحاق یعقوب را زاده یعقوب یهود و برادرانش
                                    را...</incipit>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_976-item1-item2">
                                <locus from="57a" to="57a">58a</locus>
                                <title key="work_703">The Gospel According to St. Mark</title>
                                <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="beginning">
                                    <locus from="57a" to="57a"> برگ ۵۷ر (folio 57a):</locus> انجیل
                                    مقدس عیسی مسیح چنانچه نوشته است مرقوس یکی ازهفتاد و دو تلمیذ او
                                    فصل اول عیسی عماد او آزموده کرده شد تلمیذان را میطلبد و شیطان را
                                    از وجود دور میکند و بیماران را شفا میدهد عیسی مسیح ابن
                                    الله...</incipit>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_976-item1-item3">
                                <locus from="94a" to="94a">94a</locus>
                                <title key="work_705">The Gospel of St. Luke</title>
                                <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="beginning">
                                    <locus from="94a" to="94a"> برگ ۹۴ر (folio 94a):</locus> انجیل
                                    مقدس عیسی مسیح چنانچه نوشته شده است لوقا یکی از هفتاد و دو تلمیذ
                                    او.</incipit>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_976-item1-item4">
                                <locus from="159a" to="159a">159a</locus>
                                <title key="work_704">The Gospel of St. John</title>
                                <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="beginning">
                                    <locus from="159a" to="159a"> برگ ۱۵۹ر (folio 159a):</locus>
                                    انجیل مقدس عیسی مسیح چنانچه نوشته است یوحنا یکی از دوازده رسول
                                    او.</incipit>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_976-item1-item5">
                                <locus from="205a" to="205a">205a</locus>
                                <title>Abstracts of the Four Gospels</title>
                                <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="beginning">
                                    <locus from="205a" to="205a"> برگ ۲۰۵ر (folio 205a):</locus> فصل
                                    اول در بیان آنکه عیسی مسیحست... .</incipit>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_976-item1-item6">
                                <locus from="208a" to="208a">208a</locus>
                                <title>Commentary on the Four Gospels</title>
                                <explicit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="216b" to="216b"> برگ ۲۱۶پ
                                        (folio 216b):</locus> حضرت عیسی پسر خداست و اینجا اندک سخن
                                    آورده شد برای نمودار که آسان شود خوانندگان را برای یافتن و پیدا
                                    کردن این راست. </explicit>
                                <colophon>No colophon</colophon>
                                <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                                <note>For another Persian translation of the Gospels held in the
                                    Rylands, see <ref
                                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6832"
                                            ><idno>Persian MS 337</idno></ref>.</note>
                            </msItem>
                        </msItem>
                    </msContents>
                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="codex">
                            <supportDesc material="chart">
                                <support>Textblock of straight-grained, ivory-coloured
                                        <material>paper</material>, with minimal external sizing and
                                    lightly polished, possibly handmade in the <placeName
                                        cert="medium" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                                        key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</placeName> with ~9
                                    laid lines per cm and no discernible chain lines.</support>
                                <extent>
                                    <measure unit="folio" quantity="215">215 folios, 5 flyleaves
                                        (ff. iii + 215 + ii)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf"
                                        unit="mm">
                                        <height>230</height>
                                        <width>150</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                    <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                                        <height>172</height>
                                        <width>81</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </extent>

                                <foliation xml:id="modern">Arabic numerals pencilled on the
                                    upper-left corners of the a sides when catalogued.</foliation>
                                <collation> Undetermined. <catchwords>Catchwords throughout most of
                                        the lower-left corners of the b
                                    sides.</catchwords></collation>
                                <condition>Text in good condition.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout columns="1" ruledLines="16" n="mistara"> Written in 1 column
                                    with 16 lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic"
                                        >misṭarah</hi> hand guide.</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink"> Written in
                                clear <material>black</material> nasta‘līq with subheaders in
                                    <material>red</material>. </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                        <decoDesc>

                            <decoNote type="marginal"><label>Ruling:</label> Margins and occasional
                                horizontal section breaks ruled in <material>red</material> double
                                lines throughout.</decoNote>
                        </decoDesc>
                        <additions>
                            <lb/>
                            <label>Marginalia:</label> Chapters identified by pencilled Latin notes,
                            albeit many trimmed.<lb/>
                            <label>Inscriptions:</label> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus>
                            bears a Latin title of the work with an Arabic <hi rend="italic"
                                >basmala</hi> underneath.<lb/>
                            <label>Bookplates:</label> The <locus from="vb" to="vb">final left
                                flyleaf b side (f. vb)</locus>: <q xml:lang="en">Bequeathed by
                                Samuel Robinson, of Wilmslow, <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                                    when="1884">1884</date></q>, with <q xml:lang="en">Class: 117; Section: 76; Prog. Nº 39155</q>.<lb/>
                            <locus from="Inner_back_cover" to="Inner_back_cover">Left
                                pastedown</locus>: <q xml:lang="en">Samuel Robinson, Blackbrook
                                Cottage, Wilmslow</q>. </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding notBefore="1850" notAfter="1884">
                                <p>Probably rebound for former owner <persName>Samuel
                                        Robinson</persName> by the <persName role="bnd"
                                        >Winstanley</persName> firm in <placeName
                                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                                        key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName> as per its stamp
                                    on the <locus from="va" to="va">final left flyleaf a side (f.
                                        va).</locus></p>
                                <p>Resewn on four recessed cord supports, with stiff-leaved
                                    endpapers of ivory adhered to red machine-made wove papers
                                    oversewn at the beginning and end. Edges trimmed, finely sprayed
                                    in dilute red earth, then decorative front-bead endbands sewn in
                                    pale gold and pink <material>silk</material> threads at <locus
                                        from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail"
                                        to="Tail">tail</locus>. Case-bound, tight-backed, in half
                                    dark brown morroco-grained goatskin
                                    <material>leather</material>, with five false bands on the
                                    spine, and double-combed 'nonpareil' marbled paper sides.</p>
                                <decoNote type="binding">Blind double-fillet lines paletted at head,
                                    tail, and beside the bands on the spine, and also along the
                                    paper facing the boards. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine"
                                        >Spine</locus> titled <lb/><q xml:lang="fa-Ltn-x-lc">NEW
                                        TESTAMENT PERSIAN</q><lb/> and <lb/><q
                                        xml:lang="fa-Ltn-x-lc">M. S. PERS.</q> in the bottom
                                    panel.</decoNote>
                                <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                                        <height>240</height>
                                        <width>160</width>
                                        <depth>40</depth>
                                    </dimensions></p>
                                <condition>Handle binding with caution. In fair condition, with
                                    extensive abrasion to the exterior joints and board
                                    edges.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                        <sealDesc>
                            <summary>Owens College Library, Manchester blind embossed stamp,
                                single-ruled.</summary>
                            <seal type="embossed" subtype="oval">
                                <decoNote type="seal_dimensions"><dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                                        <height>19</height>
                                        <width>21</width>
                                    </dimensions></decoNote>
                            </seal>
                        </sealDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>Probably completed in the <origPlace cert="medium"
                                ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                                >Indian subcontinent</origPlace>; undated, but probably <origDate
                                cert="medium" calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1775" notAfter="1825"
                                >late 18th to early 19th centuries CE</origDate>.</origin>
                        <provenance><p>While the circumstances under which this volume arrived in
                                Britain remain unclear, an unidentified European owner acquired the volume who
                                wrote Latin notations therein.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Subsequently obtained by <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                                    key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName> merchant and scholar
                                    <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/62917704" key="person_62917704">Samuel
                                    Robinson (1794–1884)</persName> of <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/1031142"
                                    key="place_1031142">Wilmslow</placeName>, the author of
                                    <title>Persian Poetry for English Readers</title> (1883),
                                acquired it and donated it to <orgName
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134928143" key="person_134928143"
                                    >Owens College</orgName>, which later evolved into the of The University of Manchester.</p></provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Transferred to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
                                    Library</orgName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1972"
                                    >1972</date> after it merged with the University of
                                Manchester.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
